1
00:00:04,440 --> 00:00:06,780
Today we look at Chemical Disinfection.

2
00:00:06,780 --> 00:00:10,940
And in particular chlorine, which is the
most widely used disinfectant globally.

3
00:00:11,950 --> 00:00:16,080
We'll explore a bit the chemistry of
chlorine and chlorine dosing.

4
00:00:16,080 --> 00:00:20,610
We'll look at different forms of chlorine,
gas, liquid, and solid.

5
00:00:20,610 --> 00:00:25,050
And review the effectiveness of a chlorine
in reducing pathogens.

6
00:00:25,050 --> 00:00:28,260
Finally we will give an example of
chlorine use in Haiti.

7
00:00:30,150 --> 00:00:33,800
Chlorine has been used for over a century
for the treatment of drinking water.

8
00:00:33,800 --> 00:00:38,140
Beginning in the UK and USA in the early
20th century.

9
00:00:38,140 --> 00:00:41,248
Today, chlorine is used in 98% of U.S.
water

10
00:00:41,248 --> 00:00:45,279
utilities and in some similarly high
numbers across the world.

11
00:00:46,680 --> 00:00:49,620
Chlorine is also widely used at the
household level.

12
00:00:49,620 --> 00:00:53,450
Of course, many households use bleach for
cleaning and laundry.

13
00:00:53,450 --> 00:00:56,965
But in surveys conducted in low and medium
income countries.

14
00:00:56,965 --> 00:01:01,380
5.6% of respondents reported added
chlorine to their

15
00:01:01,380 --> 00:01:03,640
drinking water to make it safer to drink.

16
00:01:04,810 --> 00:01:06,340
This was the second most common

17
00:01:06,340 --> 00:01:09,990
household water treatment practice
mentioned, after boiling.

18
00:01:09,990 --> 00:01:13,920
And was particularly high in Latin
American and Caribbean countries.

19
00:01:15,700 --> 00:01:17,740
Chlorine is a strong oxidant.

20
00:01:17,740 --> 00:01:19,930
And it reacts rapidly with different kinds
of

21
00:01:19,930 --> 00:01:25,180
organic material, including cell wall,
DNA, and enzymes.

22
00:01:25,180 --> 00:01:26,260
That's also why it's good at

23
00:01:26,260 --> 00:01:29,660
cleaning things, it really destroys
organic compounds.

24
00:01:30,660 --> 00:01:33,610
But actually in part because it's so
reactive, the

25
00:01:33,610 --> 00:01:38,330
key mechanisms in pathogen inactivation
are not well understood.

26
00:01:38,330 --> 00:01:40,730
Especially for viruses and protozoa.

27
00:01:42,550 --> 00:01:45,499
When we talk about chlorine, we can refer
to many different things.

28
00:01:46,640 --> 00:01:49,210
Large drinking water utilities typically
use

29
00:01:49,210 --> 00:01:52,340
elemental chlorine, present as chlorine
gas.

30
00:01:52,340 --> 00:01:57,080
Which is cost effective, and includes, by
definition, 100% chlorine.

31
00:01:58,350 --> 00:02:00,870
The next most concentrated form, also used
in

32
00:02:00,870 --> 00:02:05,780
many utilities, is high test hypochlorite,
or HTH.

33
00:02:05,780 --> 00:02:11,160
Which contains about 60 to 70% chlorine
and comes in powders or tablets.

34
00:02:12,710 --> 00:02:15,440
Bleaching powder or chlorinated lime or

35
00:02:15,440 --> 00:02:18,640
calcium hypochlorite is another powdered
form.

36
00:02:18,640 --> 00:02:23,060
And is often marketed as around 35%
chlorine.

37
00:02:23,060 --> 00:02:27,350
But the chlorine isn't stable and actual
concentrations vary widely.

38
00:02:27,350 --> 00:02:28,988
Sometimes as low as 15%.

39
00:02:28,988 --> 00:02:31,880
It makes calculating doses difficult.

40
00:02:33,700 --> 00:02:40,190
Household bleach is a solution of sodium
hypochlorite, usually around 5% chlorine.

41
00:02:40,190 --> 00:02:43,970
And Javel water is a similar product,
typically a little bit less strong.

42
00:02:45,840 --> 00:02:48,790
Finally, it's possible to make chlorine
locally by

43
00:02:48,790 --> 00:02:51,880
passing in an electrical current through
simple salt solution.

44
00:02:52,980 --> 00:02:55,890
This usually results in something less
than 1% chlorine.

45
00:02:58,530 --> 00:03:00,920
Whatever the chlorine source, when it is
added

46
00:03:00,920 --> 00:03:06,050
to water, it becomes hypochlorous acid, or
HOCl.

47
00:03:06,050 --> 00:03:10,210
And hypochlorous acid loses a proton at
higher pH

48
00:03:10,210 --> 00:03:14,330
and becomes hypochlorite or OCl, with a
negative charge.

49
00:03:15,830 --> 00:03:19,018
These two species together are called Free
Chlorine.

50
00:03:19,018 --> 00:03:26,300
At pH 7.54, the two species are present in
equal amount.

51
00:03:27,700 --> 00:03:31,040
At higher pH, hypochlorite dominates.

52
00:03:31,040 --> 00:03:35,210
While at lower pH, hypochlorous acid is the
main species.

53
00:03:36,630 --> 00:03:39,810
This is important because hypochlorous
acid, the one with

54
00:03:39,810 --> 00:03:45,200
the proton attached, is a much stronger
disinfectant than hypochlorite.

55
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:48,180
For this reason it's recommended that
water should always have

56
00:03:48,180 --> 00:03:52,560
a pH of less than eight when chlorination
is being applied.

57
00:03:52,560 --> 00:03:57,610
So that there's a, a reasonable amount of
hypochlorous acid present.

58
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:02,970
Chlorine is highly reactive, and when
added to water, a lot

59
00:04:02,970 --> 00:04:06,610
of the chlorine will react with natural
chemicals in the water.

60
00:04:06,610 --> 00:04:11,130
So, the dose have to big enough to meet
both the chlorine demand of the water.

61
00:04:11,130 --> 00:04:15,280
And to produce a residual that is strong
enough to kill the target pathogens.

62
00:04:16,840 --> 00:04:19,170
Chlorine demand can be caused by organic

63
00:04:19,170 --> 00:04:22,550
carbon, which is naturally present in
surface waters.

64
00:04:22,550 --> 00:04:25,770
But also by iron and manganese, or
ammonia,

65
00:04:25,770 --> 00:04:28,069
which tends to be more present in ground
water.

66
00:04:29,640 --> 00:04:31,970
It's normally recommend that to have a
residual

67
00:04:31,970 --> 00:04:36,620
concentration of at least 0.5 milligrams
per liter.

68
00:04:36,620 --> 00:04:40,200
And this can require a dose of any where
from one to

69
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:45,199
five milligrams per liter with two
milligrams per liter being fairly typical.

70
00:04:46,780 --> 00:04:49,860
Turbidity reduces the effectiveness of
chlorine both

71
00:04:49,860 --> 00:04:53,860
by shielding pathogens directly and by
consuming chlorine.

72
00:04:53,860 --> 00:04:58,280
So standard doses are normally doubled
when the water is turbid.

73
00:04:58,280 --> 00:05:02,290
Ideally, the right dose will be determined
through trial and error.

74
00:05:02,290 --> 00:05:04,780
By adding different amounts of chlorine to
the water

75
00:05:04,780 --> 00:05:08,160
to be treated to see what yields the
desired residual.

76
00:05:09,930 --> 00:05:14,130
Chlorine doesn't pose any health risk,
health risks itself

77
00:05:14,130 --> 00:05:17,820
though the concentrated forms can be
dangerous to handle.

78
00:05:17,820 --> 00:05:22,070
WHO does list a guideline value of five mg
per liter.

79
00:05:22,070 --> 00:05:25,220
But this is conservative and would
probably result in

80
00:05:25,220 --> 00:05:28,689
unacceptable tastes or odors at this level
in any case.

81
00:05:30,850 --> 00:05:34,340
The use of chlorine in household water
treatment was first developed by

82
00:05:34,340 --> 00:05:38,570
the US Centers for Disease Control, and
the Pan American Health Organization.

83
00:05:39,610 --> 00:05:43,150
They proposed an intervention, including
three elements.

84
00:05:43,150 --> 00:05:49,410
Chlorine disinfection, and this was later
expanded to include other HWTS processes.

85
00:05:49,410 --> 00:05:52,750
Safe storage, and behavior change
communication.

86
00:05:54,350 --> 00:05:56,630
This model has been widely taken up,

87
00:05:56,630 --> 00:06:00,160
especially through Latin America and parts
of Africa.

88
00:06:00,160 --> 00:06:02,760
And typically involves production of a
dilute

89
00:06:02,760 --> 00:06:09,480
sodium hypochlorite solution around 0.75%
free chlorine.

90
00:06:09,480 --> 00:06:14,680
Now, because hypochlorous acid is much
more reactive and also more volatile

91
00:06:14,680 --> 00:06:20,330
than hypochlorite, the shelf life is much
longer at high pH.

92
00:06:20,330 --> 00:06:25,600
So these solutions are typically
stabilized at pH 11 or greater.

93
00:06:25,600 --> 00:06:30,350
For similar reasons household bleach has a
pH around, of around 12.

94
00:06:30,350 --> 00:06:32,100
And it's slightly irritating to the skin.

95
00:06:33,990 --> 00:06:38,480
In different countries, different brand of
liquid chlorine are promoted.

96
00:06:38,480 --> 00:06:40,820
Some of the common brand names are Water

97
00:06:40,820 --> 00:06:46,190
Guard, Clorin, Claro and in Francophone
countries, Sur Eau.

98
00:06:49,660 --> 00:06:52,810
The bottles are normally designed so that
one capful

99
00:06:52,810 --> 00:06:56,060
is a good dose for the locally used
storage containers.

100
00:06:57,090 --> 00:07:03,007
For example, a five milliliter capful of
0.75% free chlorine

101
00:07:03,007 --> 00:07:09,880
added to a 20 liter jerrycan gives a dose
of 1.9 milligrams per liter.

102
00:07:09,880 --> 00:07:13,550
And, again, this dose should be doubled if
the raw water is turbid.

103
00:07:15,380 --> 00:07:17,030
There is another form of chlorine

104
00:07:17,030 --> 00:07:19,650
which isn't used in conventional water
treatment.

105
00:07:19,650 --> 00:07:25,040
But is popular in swimming pools and
increasingly in household water treatment.

106
00:07:25,040 --> 00:07:26,760
This is a chemical with a long name.

107
00:07:26,760 --> 00:07:30,290
It's called sodium dichloroisocyanurate.

108
00:07:30,290 --> 00:07:34,590
So you can see why people call it NaDCC
instead.

109
00:07:34,590 --> 00:07:37,058
And it's about 60% free chlorine by
weight.

110
00:07:37,058 --> 00:07:41,600
The other 40% is a chemical, cyanuric
acid,

111
00:07:41,600 --> 00:07:44,709
which bonds with free chlorine and
provides a reservoir.

112
00:07:45,780 --> 00:07:48,150
Thus, as free chlorine is consumed

113
00:07:48,150 --> 00:07:51,970
through chlorine demand or inactivation of
pathogens.

114
00:07:51,970 --> 00:07:55,690
The reservoir can release more free
chlorine into the water.

115
00:07:57,430 --> 00:08:00,540
Cyanuric acid itself doesn't pose a health
risk.

116
00:08:00,540 --> 00:08:04,800
The guideline value of 40 milligrams per
liter is well

117
00:08:04,800 --> 00:08:07,600
above levels that would be reached in
drinking water treatment.

118
00:08:09,270 --> 00:08:13,340
Because of this reservoir effect, any DCC
allows

119
00:08:13,340 --> 00:08:16,790
a more steady and consistent free chlorine
level.

120
00:08:16,790 --> 00:08:20,609
Which may lead to fewer reports of taste
and odor problems.

121
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:27,610
NADCC is produced in the form of
effervescent tablets or fizzy

122
00:08:27,610 --> 00:08:31,800
tablets, which are individually wrapped
and have a long shelf life.

123
00:08:32,830 --> 00:08:35,280
They come in a wide range of
concentrations.

124
00:08:35,280 --> 00:08:40,260
The most popular are 33 and 66 milligram
versions.

125
00:08:40,260 --> 00:08:44,470
Which are good for 10 or 20 liters of
water, respectively.

126
00:08:46,200 --> 00:08:48,780
Aquatabs, shown here, is one of the
leading

127
00:08:48,780 --> 00:08:51,080
brands globally, but there are others as
well.

128
00:08:53,440 --> 00:08:58,970
NaDCC tablets are easy to use and have
proven particularly popular in emergency

129
00:08:58,970 --> 00:09:04,140
settings But now are increasingly used
routinely at the household level.

130
00:09:06,010 --> 00:09:10,040
Chlorine efficacy, like other
disinfectants is a combination

131
00:09:10,040 --> 00:09:13,700
of the concentration and the time of
exposure.

132
00:09:13,700 --> 00:09:16,170
For chlorine the dose can be expressed as
a

133
00:09:16,170 --> 00:09:20,200
CT value in units of minute, milligrams
per liter.

134
00:09:22,220 --> 00:09:25,220
For conventional drinking water treatment,
a common goal is to

135
00:09:25,220 --> 00:09:30,090
have a residual of 0.5 milligrams per
liter free chlorine.

136
00:09:30,090 --> 00:09:34,480
In contact with water for at least 30
minutes to ensure a good pathogen kill.

137
00:09:35,970 --> 00:09:41,730
Multiplying these together gives a Ct
